\begin{problem}{1.1}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
The constraints of the utility maximization problem are as follows:
$$
\max_{b, c} bc
$$
such that
$$
2b + 10c = 100, b \geq 0, c \geq 0.
$$
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.2}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Utility maximization is achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_b}{U_c} = \frac{p_b}{p_c}.
$$
Note that $U_b = c$ and $U_c = b$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{c}{b} = \frac{2}{10},
$$
or $b = 5c$. Substituting this into the budget constraint shows that $10c + 10c = 100$, or $c = 5$. This then means that $2b + 10(5) = 100$, and $b = 25$. In other words, the consumer buys 25 bottles of beer and 5 packs of cigarettes.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.3}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Diagrams:
