\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.4}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Given that the consumer bought $25$ bottles of beer and $5$ cigarettes, the compensation with the new prices would give $1$ dollar for each bottle of beer and $10$ dollars for each pack of cigarettes. This means that the individual's new budget is \$75, exactly enough to buy the original bundle at the new price.

This compensation is an example of Slutsky compensation because the income has been adjusted such that the consumer can just barely access the old bundle before the price change, as opposed to preserving utility as Hicksian compensation does.
\end{proof}

