\begin{problem}{1.6}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
The constraints of the new utility maximization problem are as follows:
$$
\max_{b, c} bc
$$
such that
$$
1b + 10c = 75, b \geq 0, c \geq 0.
$$
Utility maximization is achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_b}{U_c} = \frac{p_b}{p_c}.
$$
Note that $U_b = c$ and $U_c = b$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{c}{b} = \frac{1}{10},
$$
or $b = 10c$. Substituting this into the budget constraint shows that $10c + 10c = 75$, or $c = 3.75$. This then means that $1b + 10(3.75) = 75$, and $b = 37.5$. In other words, the consumer buys 37.5 bottles of beer and 3.75 packs of cigarettes.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.7}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
The substitution effect of the decrease in the price of beer lead the consumer to purchase more bottles of beer. They increased their consumption of beer by 12.5 bottles, from 25 to 37.5. On the other hand, their consumption of cigarettes has decreased by 1.25 packs, going from 5 packs to 3.75.
\end{proof}

