\frac{c}{b} = \frac{1}{10},
$$
as derived in part 1.6 still stands. Then, substituting this into the budget equation $1b + 10c = 100$ shows us that $5 = c$, and $b = 50$. In other words, the consumer purchases 5 packs of cigarettes and 50 bottles of beer at the new prices and at the original budget.
\end{proof}

