\begin{problem}{1.10}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Observe that in the original solution (1.2), 25 bottles of beer and 5 packs of cigarettes are purchased, and using the utility function $bc$, the individual achieves a utility of 125. Then, the question is how can expenditure be minimized such that this utility is achieved? The constraints of the expenditure minimization problem are as follows:
$$
\min_{b, c} 1b + 10c
$$
such that
$$
125 = bc.
$$

Expenditure minimization is achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_b}{U_c} = \frac{p_b}{p_c}.
$$
Note that $U_b = c$ and $U_c = b$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{c}{b} = \frac{1}{10},
$$
or $b = 10c$. Substituting this into the utility constraint shows that $10c^2 = 125$, or $c = 3.5355$. Then, to achieve utility 125, the minimum number of beers required is $125/3.5355 = 35.3556$. Thus, we conclude that the new income level is $3*(3.5355)+35.3556 = 70.7114$ dollars.

This compensation is an example of Hicksian compensation because the income is to be adjusted such that the consumer can barely access the same level of utility as previously, compared to Slutsky compensation which would compensate the user such that they can just barely buy the original bundle.
\end{proof}

