\begin{problem}{1.16}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
See graph on 1.3. In the first case with the Slutsky compensation, the substitution effect is greater than the substitution effect component of the Hicksian compensation graph. On the other hand, the income effect is greater on the Hicksian compensation graph compared to the income effect on the Slutsky compensation.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.17}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Slutsky compensation has a greater substitution effect than the Hicksian compensation. As we can see from the previous part, the substitution effect component of the Slutsky compensation is greater than the substitution effect component on the Hicksian compensation graph. This disparity is a result of the fact that Slutsky compensation enables the budget to increase in order to access the original bundle, reducing the income effect. This is critical as, as seen in 1.16, a lower income effect means a greater substitution effect as these two components sum up to each other. Slutsky compensation is often described as overcompensating for changes in price because it provides the consumer with a hightened budget that enables them to find bundles that have a utility that exceeds the utility of the original bundle.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.18}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Hicksian compensation has a greater income effect than the Slutsky compensation. As we can see from the previous part, the income effect component of the Hicksian compensation is greater than the income effect component on the Slutsky compensation graph. This disparity is a result of the fact Hicksian compensation affords the user a smaller budget in general, increasing the effect of the change in budget. Thus, in general Hicksian compensation yields a greater income effect compared to Slutsky compensation.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{1.19}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
The decomposition of a change in price into an income and a substitution effect is important because it enables us to observe the induced effect of a price change. A greater substitution effect suggests that consumers are more significantly changing their consumption habits as a result of the price change. A greater income effect on the other hand suggests that the change in a consumer's budget is the driving force behind determining which bundle they consume in the end.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{2}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
We are given that
$$
x_m(p_x, p_y, m) = x_h(p_x, p_y, v(p_x, p_y, m)).
$$
Taking the partial derivative of both sides with respect to $p_x$ shows that
$$
\frac{\partial x_m}{\partial p_x} = \frac{\partial x_h}{\partial p_x} + \frac{\partial x_h}{\partial v}\frac{\partial v}{\partial p_x},
$$
With the right hand side being derived from the fact that the rate of change right hand side as a result of a change in $p_x$ is a combination of its effect on $X$ in addition to its effect on $E$, which then effects $X$. Next, observe that 
$$
\frac{\partial v}{\partial p_x} = x,
$$
because the expenditure function is linear, and the only component that contains the variable $p_x$ is the component $p_xx$. It is clear that increasing the price $p_x$ will increase expenditure at a rate $x$. Substituting this into the original equation shows that
$$
\frac{\partial x_m}{\partial p_x} = \frac{\partial x_h}{\partial p_x} + x\frac{\partial x_h}{\partial v}.
$$
Next, observe that a change in $M$ is equivalent to the change in expenditures $E$, because these two are implied to be the same as the consumption is on the budget line. Thus,
$$
\frac{\partial x_m}{\partial p_x} = \frac{\partial x_h}{\partial p_x} + x\frac{\partial x_h}{\partial e}.
$$
$$
\frac{\partial x_h}{\partial p_x} =  \frac{\partial x_m}{\partial p_x} - x\frac{\partial x_h}{\partial e}.
$$
This is the Slutsky equation because $\frac{\partial x_h}{\partial p_x}$ represents the total effect of the consumption of $x$ as $p_x$ changes, $\frac{\partial x_m}{\partial p_x}$ represents the substitution effect as it represents the change in the consumption bundle independent of the change in expenditure, and lastly $x\frac{\partial x_h}{\partial e}$ represents the income effect because it tracks the change in the consumption of $x$ as a result of the change in expenditure.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3.1}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
The constraints of Peter's utility maximization problem are as follows:
$$
\max_{c, r} 3log(c) + r
$$
such that
$$
5c + 4r = 60.
$$
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3.2}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Utility maximization is achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_c}{U_r} = \frac{p_c}{p_r}.
$$
Note that $U_c = \frac{\partial}{\partial c}(3ln(c)) = \frac{3}{c}$ and $U_r = 1$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{3}{c} = \frac{5}{4},
$$
or $c = \frac{12}{5}$. Substituting this into the budget constraint shows that $5(12/5) + 4r = 60$, or $r= 12$. In other words, peter consumes $\frac{12}{5}$ pounds of cereal and $12$ pounds of raisins.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3.3}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Diagram:
\vspace{8 cm}
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3.4}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Given that the original bundle is $12$ pounds of raisins and $12/5$ pounds of cereal, at the new price where both goods are 4 dollars, the budget required such that he can still barely afford his original consumption bundle is $57.6$ dollars.

Utility maximization is still achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_c}{U_r} = \frac{p_c}{p_r}.
$$
Note that still, $U_c = \frac{\partial}{\partial c}(3ln(c)) = \frac{3}{c}$ and $U_r = 1$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{3}{c} = 1,
$$
or $c = 3$. Substituting this into the budget constraint shows that $4(3) + 4r = 57.6$, or $r= 11.4$. In other words, Peter consumes $3$ pounds of cereal and $11.4$ pounds of raisins. See 3.3 for graph.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3.5}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Given that the original bundle is $12$ pounds of raisins and $12/5$ pounds of cereal, the original utility was $3ln(12/5) + 12 = 14.6264$. 

Note that expenditure minimization is still achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_c}{U_r} = \frac{p_c}{p_r}.
$$
Note that still, $U_c = \frac{\partial}{\partial c}(3ln(c)) = \frac{3}{c}$ and $U_r = 1$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{3}{c} = 1,
$$
or $c = 3$. Substituting this into the utility constraint $3log(c) + r =14.6264$, we get that $r = 11.3305$. Thus, Peter consumes $3$ pounds of cereal and $11.3305$ pounds of raisins. See 3.3 for graph.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{3.6}
\end{problem}
\begin{proof}
Utility maximization is achieved when 
$$
\frac{U_c}{U_r} = \frac{p_c}{p_r}.
$$
Note that $U_c = \frac{\partial}{\partial c}(3ln(c)) = \frac{3}{c}$ and $U_r = 1$. Thus, utility is maximized when 
$$
\frac{3}{c} = 1,
$$
or $c = 3$. Substituting this into the budget constraint shows that $4c + 4r = 60$, or $r= 12$. In other words, peter consumes $3$ pounds of cereal and $12$ pounds of raisins. Compared to the results from 3.4, 3.5, this bundle has more pounds of raisins. However, interestingly, the pounds of cereal is always preserved at 3. It then follows that this bundle yields more utility than those derived in 3.4, 3.5.
